      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where particles become linked so that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of distance. Unlike classical correlations, which arise from shared history or predetermined properties, entanglement creates a unified quantum state where the properties are undefined until measured. This fundamental difference means entangled systems cannot be described by local hidden variables, a fact famously highlighted by Bell's Theorem.",
