      "content": "that makes sense but it still feels super weird. like how does the info even get there instantly? i read somewhere that einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it didn't seem to follow normal rules. can u explain why he thought it was so spooky?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein found it \"spooky\" because he believed the universe must be \"local,\" meaning objects can only be influenced by their immediate surroundings, not instantly across vast distances. Since information cannot travel faster than light within classical physics, entanglement seemed to violate this fundamental limit by allowing instantaneous connection between distant particles. He struggled with this because it challenged his belief in \"realism,\" the idea that objects possess definite properties even before they are observed.",
